data.content:
Yes — MSTest v3.3+ supports **ValueTuples** with `[DynamicData]`, giving you compile-time type safety without `object[]`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:**
- `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>` — no boxing, type-checked at compile time
- Square bracket array literals → parenthesized tuples
- The test method signature stays the same; MSTest destructures the tuple into the parameters automatically

If you have more complex data, MSTest v3.8+ also offers `[TestDataSource<T>]` where `T` is a custom type, but tuples cover most cases cleanly.
